{:title "Redesign Workflows: Use-Case Targeted with Safety by Default"
 :version "1.0.0"
 :priority :high
 :context
 "CRITICAL INSIGHT from dogfooding: The current complexity-based workflow system
  (simple/lean/canonical) is fundamentally flawed. The :simple workflow skips
  essential safeguards (testing, PR monitoring, review gates) that should be
  present in ALL workflows, regardless of task size.

  Discovered during dashboard build: spec without explicit workflow type defaulted
  to :simple (due to parser bug, now fixed), which would have skipped tests and
  PR monitoring for a production-critical feature.

  NEW ARCHITECTURE: Use-case targeted workflows with safety built-in by default.
  Every workflow includes cognitive safety, testing, PR monitoring, and review
  gates. The difference is in the APPROACH, not the presence of safety features."

 :description
 "Replace complexity-based workflows (simple, lean, canonical) with use-case
  targeted workflows that match developer intent. Every workflow includes safety
  features by default - the variation is in approach (iteration style, review
  depth, planning rigor) not in whether safety exists.

  Current problems:
  - :simple skips tests, PR monitoring, review gates (unsafe!)
  - :lean vs :canonical is unclear to users (when to use which?)
  - Complexity-based naming doesn't match user mental models
  - No workflow for common use cases (bugfix, docs, feature, refactor)

  New approach:
  - Workflows named after USE CASES (bugfix, feature, refactor, docs, experiment)
  - ALL workflows include: tests, linting, PR monitoring, review gates
  - Variation is in APPROACH: iteration speed, review depth, planning style
  - Clear mapping from user intent to workflow type"

 :intent
 {:type :architectural-redesign
  :scope ["Remove simple/lean/canonical workflows"
          "Implement 5 use-case targeted workflows"
          "Update workflow selector logic"
          "Migrate existing specs"
          "Update documentation"]

  :success-criteria
  ["All workflows include safety features by default"
   "Workflow selection matches user intent clearly"
   "No workflows skip tests, linting, or PR monitoring"
   "Backward compatibility via migration"
   "Comprehensive documentation"
   "Dogfood with real tasks successfully"]}

 :proposed-workflows
 {:bugfix
  {:name "Bugfix Workflow"
   :id :bugfix-v1
   :description
   "Fast iteration for bug fixes with full safety.

    Approach:
    - Quick diagnosis and fix
    - Test-driven: write failing test, fix bug, verify
    - Single PR with clear before/after
    - Automated review gates
    - Monitoring for regression

    Safety features (always included):
    - ✅ Test coverage required
    - ✅ Linting must pass
    - ✅ PR monitoring
    - ✅ Review checklist
    - ✅ Regression testing"

   :phases
   [:diagnosis      ; Analyze error, identify root cause
    :reproduction   ; Create minimal failing test
    :fix            ; Implement fix
    :verification   ; Run full test suite
    :pr-review      ; Create PR, monitor until merged
    :post-merge]    ; Verify fix in production

   :characteristics
   {:iteration-speed :fast          ; Quick cycles
    :review-depth :automated        ; Automated checks + human review
    :planning-rigor :minimal        ; Just enough planning
    :pr-strategy :single-pr         ; One PR for the fix
    :risk-tolerance :low}           ; Bug fixes must be safe

   :when-to-use
   ["Fixing a specific bug or error"
    "Addressing regression"
    "Patching security vulnerability"
    "Correcting incorrect behavior"]}

  :feature
  {:name "Feature Workflow"
   :id :feature-v1
   :description
   "Iterative feature development with comprehensive review.

    Approach:
    - Design → Implement → Test → Review cycle
    - Multi-PR if needed (feature flags, incremental rollout)
    - Comprehensive testing (unit, integration, E2E)
    - Design review + code review
    - Metrics and monitoring

    Safety features (always included):
    - ✅ Design review checkpoint
    - ✅ Comprehensive test coverage
    - ✅ Linting and type checking
    - ✅ PR monitoring with risk analysis
    - ✅ Review gates (design + code + QA)
    - ✅ Feature flags for safe rollout
    - ✅ Metrics and observability"

   :phases
   [:design         ; Design review, architecture decisions
    :implementation ; Iterative development with tests
    :testing        ; Comprehensive test coverage
    :integration    ; Integration testing
    :pr-review      ; PR creation, review, monitoring
    :post-merge     ; Monitoring, metrics, rollout
    ]

   :characteristics
   {:iteration-speed :moderate      ; Balanced pace
    :review-depth :comprehensive    ; Design + code + QA
    :planning-rigor :thorough       ; Upfront design work
    :pr-strategy :multi-pr-allowed  ; Can split into multiple PRs
    :risk-tolerance :low-to-medium} ; Features should be stable

   :when-to-use
   ["Adding new functionality"
    "Building new component or service"
    "Implementing user-facing features"
    "Multi-phase development needed"]}

  :refactor
  {:name "Refactoring Workflow"
   :id :refactor-v1
   :description
   "Systematic refactoring with behavior preservation.

    Approach:
    - Analysis → Plan → Refactor → Verify cycle
    - Stratified design principles (≤3 layers, ≤400 lines)
    - Multi-PR with dependencies (layered refactoring)
    - Behavior-preserving transformations
    - Comprehensive regression testing

    Safety features (always included):
    - ✅ Baseline tests before refactoring
    - ✅ Behavior preservation verification
    - ✅ Stratification analysis
    - ✅ Linting and complexity metrics
    - ✅ PR dependency tracking
    - ✅ Regression test suite
    - ✅ Code review with before/after comparison"

   :phases
   [:analysis       ; Analyze current structure, identify issues
    :planning       ; Plan refactoring strategy (layers, PRs)
    :baseline       ; Establish test baseline
    :refactoring    ; Iterative refactoring with tests
    :verification   ; Verify behavior preservation
    :pr-review      ; Multi-PR with dependencies
    :post-merge]    ; Verify system still works

   :characteristics
   {:iteration-speed :deliberate    ; Careful, methodical
    :review-depth :comprehensive    ; Architecture + code review
    :planning-rigor :high           ; Detailed refactoring plan
    :pr-strategy :multi-pr-phased   ; Phased PRs with dependencies
    :risk-tolerance :very-low}      ; Must preserve behavior

   :when-to-use
   ["Improving code structure"
    "Applying stratified design"
    "Reducing complexity"
    "Extracting components"
    "Following Rule 720 or Rule 210"]}

  :docs
  {:name "Documentation Workflow"
   :id :docs-v1
   :description
   "Documentation updates with quality review.

    Approach:
    - Write → Review → Publish cycle
    - Single PR with clear scope
    - Quality checks (spelling, links, formatting)
    - Review for accuracy and clarity
    - Monitoring for doc health

    Safety features (always included):
    - ✅ Spelling and grammar checks
    - ✅ Link validation
    - ✅ Formatting verification
    - ✅ Technical accuracy review
    - ✅ PR monitoring
    - ✅ Post-publish verification"

   :phases
   [:writing        ; Write documentation
    :review         ; Technical + editorial review
    :validation     ; Check links, formatting, spelling
    :pr-review      ; Create PR, get approvals
    :post-merge]    ; Verify docs render correctly

   :characteristics
   {:iteration-speed :fast          ; Quick turnaround
    :review-depth :editorial        ; Technical + editorial
    :planning-rigor :minimal        ; Light planning
    :pr-strategy :single-pr         ; One PR per doc change
    :risk-tolerance :medium}        ; Docs are lower risk

   :when-to-use
   ["Writing documentation"
    "Updating README or guides"
    "Adding code comments"
    "Creating tutorials"
    "Documentation-only changes"]}

  :experiment
  {:name "Experimental Workflow"
   :id :experiment-v1
   :description
   "Rapid prototyping with safety guardrails.

    Approach:
    - Explore → Validate → Decide cycle
    - Feature branch (no merge to main initially)
    - Quick iteration, tolerate rough edges
    - Decision checkpoint before production
    - If viable → promote to feature workflow

    Safety features (always included):
    - ✅ Isolated feature branch
    - ✅ Basic linting (can be relaxed)
    - ✅ Decision checkpoint before merge
    - ✅ PR review if promoted
    - ✅ Clear experiment vs production boundary"

   :phases
   [:exploration    ; Rapid prototyping
    :validation     ; Test feasibility
    :decision       ; Go/no-go checkpoint
    :cleanup        ; If go: clean up for production
    :promotion]     ; Promote to feature workflow or discard

   :characteristics
   {:iteration-speed :very-fast     ; Rapid prototyping
    :review-depth :minimal          ; Focus on feasibility
    :planning-rigor :none           ; Explore first
    :pr-strategy :feature-branch    ; No main merge initially
    :risk-tolerance :high}          ; Experiments can fail

   :when-to-use
   ["Prototyping new ideas"
    "Testing feasibility"
    "Exploring alternatives"
    "Spike solutions"
    "Research and discovery"]}

  :implementation-plan
  {:phase-1-workflow-definitions
   {:title "Define New Workflow Structures"
    :deliverables
    ["Create workflows/bugfix-v1.edn"
     "Create workflows/feature-v1.edn"
     "Create workflows/refactor-v1.edn"
     "Create workflows/docs-v1.edn"
     "Create workflows/experiment-v1.edn"
     "Each workflow includes full phase definitions"
     "Safety features documented in metadata"]

    :files-to-create
    ["components/workflow/resources/workflows/bugfix-v1.edn"
     "components/workflow/resources/workflows/feature-v1.edn"
     "components/workflow/resources/workflows/refactor-v1.edn"
     "components/workflow/resources/workflows/docs-v1.edn"
     "components/workflow/resources/workflows/experiment-v1.edn"]

    :structure-template
    {:workflow/id :bugfix-v1
     :workflow/name "Bugfix Workflow"
     :workflow/description "Fast iteration for bug fixes"
     :workflow/version "1.0.0"
     :workflow/characteristics {:iteration-speed :fast
                                :review-depth :automated
                                :planning-rigor :minimal}
     :workflow/safety-features
     [:test-coverage :linting :pr-monitoring :review-gates]
     :workflow/phases
     [{:phase/id :diagnosis
       :phase/name "Diagnosis"
       :phase/description "Analyze error and identify root cause"
       :phase/agent-role :diagnostician
       :phase/outputs [:root-cause-analysis :reproduction-steps]
       :phase/safety-checks [:linting-passed]}
      {:phase/id :reproduction
       :phase/name "Reproduction"
       :phase/description "Create minimal failing test"
       :phase/agent-role :test-engineer
       :phase/outputs [:failing-test]
       :phase/safety-checks [:test-actually-fails]}
      ;; ... more phases
      ]}}

   :phase-2-selector-redesign
   {:title "Redesign Workflow Selector"
    :deliverables
    ["Update bases/cli/src/ai/miniforge/cli/workflow_selector.clj"
     "New selection rules for use-case workflows"
     "Remove simple/lean/canonical rules"
     "Add intent-based matching (bugfix, feature, refactor, docs, experiment)"
     "Confidence scoring for each workflow"
     "Fallback to :feature-v1 (safest general-purpose)"]

    :selection-algorithm
    {:rules
     [{:conditions [[:type :bugfix]
                    [:keywords #{:bug :fix :regression}]]
       :select :bugfix-v1
       :confidence :high
       :reason "Bug fix detected from type or keywords"}

      {:conditions [[:type :refactoring]
                    [:keywords #{:refactor :stratified-design}]
                    [:constraints #{:rule-720 :rule-210}]]
       :select :refactor-v1
       :confidence :high
       :reason "Refactoring detected from type, keywords, or constraints"}

      {:conditions [[:type :docs]
                    [:keywords #{:documentation :docs-only}]
                    [:file-scope #{:markdown-only :readme-only}]]
       :select :docs-v1
       :confidence :high
       :reason "Documentation-only change detected"}

      {:conditions [[:keywords #{:experiment :prototype :spike :explore}]]
       :select :experiment-v1
       :confidence :medium
       :reason "Experimental nature detected"}

      {:conditions [[:type :feature]
                    [:keywords #{:feature :new-functionality}]
                    [:default true]]
       :select :feature-v1
       :confidence :medium
       :reason "Feature development (default for unknown types)"}]

     :default-workflow :feature-v1
     :default-reason "Safe general-purpose workflow with all safety features"}}

   :phase-3-migration
   {:title "Migrate Existing Workflows and Specs"
    :deliverables
    ["Create migration map: simple→feature, lean→feature, canonical→refactor"
     "Update all existing workflow specs in work/"
     "Deprecate old workflow files"
     "Add migration warnings to workflow loader"]

    :migration-strategy
    {:simple-sdlc-v1 :feature-v1
     :lean-sdlc-v1 :feature-v1
     :canonical-sdlc-v1 :refactor-v1}

    :files-to-update
    ["work/*.edn - Update any specs with old workflow types"
     "components/workflow/resources/workflows/simple-sdlc-v1.edn - DEPRECATE"
     "components/workflow/resources/workflows/lean-sdlc-v1.edn - DEPRECATE"
     "components/workflow/resources/workflows/canonical-sdlc-v1.edn - DEPRECATE"]

    :deprecation-period "90 days with migration warnings"}}

  :technical-details
  {:workflow-structure
   "Each workflow is a self-contained EDN file with:
   - Workflow metadata (id, name, version, description)
   - Characteristics (iteration speed, review depth, planning rigor)
   - Safety features (always present, documented explicitly)
   - Phase definitions (phase graph with dependencies)
   - Agent role assignments per phase
   - Success criteria and exit conditions"

   :safety-by-default
   "ALL workflows include these safety features (no exceptions):
   - Test coverage requirements (may vary by workflow)
   - Linting and code quality checks
   - PR creation and monitoring
   - Review gates (automated or human)
   - Post-merge verification

   The difference between workflows is HOW these are applied:
   - :bugfix-v1: Fast iteration, automated checks, single PR
   - :feature-v1: Comprehensive testing, design review, multi-PR allowed
   - :refactor-v1: Behavior preservation, stratification, phased PRs
   - :docs-v1: Editorial review, link validation, quick turnaround
   - :experiment-v1: Isolated branch, decision checkpoint, promotion path"

   :selection-confidence
   "Workflow selector returns confidence score:
   - :high (>90%) - Clear match from explicit type or strong keywords
   - :medium (70-90%) - Inferred from description or context
   - :low (<70%) - Fallback to default :feature-v1

   Always show reasoning to user:
   'ℹ️  Auto-selected workflow: bugfix-v1 (high confidence)
       Reason: Bug fix detected from :type :bugfix
       Override with :workflow/type in your spec'"

   :backward-compatibility
   "Graceful migration path:
   - Old workflow types trigger deprecation warning
   - Automatic mapping to new workflow types
   - 90-day deprecation period before removal
   - Migration guide in documentation
   - Specs can opt-in early with :workflow/type :bugfix-v1"}

  :testing-strategy
  {:unit-tests
   ["Test workflow selector rules for each use case"
    "Verify safety features present in all workflows"
    "Test migration mapping for old workflow types"
    "Validate workflow file structure"]

   :integration-tests
   ["Run each workflow end-to-end with test specs"
    "Verify PR creation and monitoring works"
    "Test phase transitions and dependencies"
    "Validate safety gates prevent unsafe merges"]

   :dogfooding
   ["Use :bugfix-v1 for small bug fixes"
    "Use :feature-v1 for new components"
    "Use :refactor-v1 for stratified design work"
    "Use :docs-v1 for documentation updates"
    "Use :experiment-v1 for prototypes"
    "Collect feedback on workflow selection accuracy"
    "Measure time-to-PR and merge success rate"]}

  :documentation
  {:user-guide
   "workflows/README.md - Comprehensive guide:
   - When to use each workflow (decision tree)
   - Safety features explained
   - How to override workflow selection
   - Examples for each workflow type
   - Migration guide from old workflows"

   :developer-guide
   "docs/architecture/workflows.md - Technical details:
   - Workflow file structure
   - Phase graph execution model
   - Safety feature implementation
   - Adding new workflow types
   - Selection algorithm internals"}

  :success-metrics
  ["✅ All workflows include safety features by default"
   "✅ Workflow selection accuracy >90% on test corpus"
   "✅ Zero workflows skip tests or PR monitoring"
   "✅ User feedback: workflow names match mental models"
   "✅ Migration from old workflows seamless"
   "✅ Dogfooding successful for all workflow types"
   "✅ Documentation comprehensive and clear"]

  :constraints
  ["Must work in Babashka (no JVM-only dependencies)"
   "All files follow Rule 720 (≤400 lines)"
   "Stratified design (Rule 210)"
   "Backward compatibility during migration period"
   "No breaking changes for existing running workflows"
   "Safety features NEVER optional or skippable"]

  :risks-and-mitigations
  [{:risk "Users miss the old simple workflow for quick tasks"
    :severity :medium
    :mitigation ":experiment-v1 provides fast iteration for prototypes, :bugfix-v1 for quick fixes. Both include safety but optimized for speed."}

   {:risk "Workflow selection picks wrong workflow"
    :severity :medium
    :mitigation "Show confidence score and reasoning, easy override with :workflow/type, collect feedback to improve rules"}

   {:risk "Migration breaks existing workflows mid-execution"
    :severity :high
    :mitigation "Running workflows continue with old definitions, only new workflows use new types. 90-day deprecation period."}

   {:risk "Safety features slow down development"
    :severity :low
    :mitigation "Safety features are non-negotiable. Optimize them (parallel tests, fast linters) but never skip them."}]

  :competitive-advantage
  "This is a critical differentiator. Other workflow engines treat safety as
  optional or advanced. We build it in by default, making it IMPOSSIBLE to
  accidentally skip tests or PR monitoring.

  Our workflows match how developers think (bugfix, feature, refactor, docs,
  experiment) rather than abstract complexity levels. This reduces cognitive
  load and increases adoption.

  The safety-by-default approach builds trust - teams can confidently use
  miniforge knowing it won't merge untested code or skip review gates."

  :deliverables
  ["5 new workflow definition files (bugfix, feature, refactor, docs, experiment)"
   "Updated workflow selector with use-case matching"
   "Migration guide and deprecation warnings"
   "Comprehensive user and developer documentation"
   "Integration tests for all workflows"
   "Dogfooding validation across multiple use cases"]

  :workflow/type :feature-v1  ; Use new feature workflow to build this!
  :workflow/version "latest"}}